“you were fine,” my mom says. 

no, i was masking as best as i could and dissolving into a suicidal mess behind every closed door i could find.

in the 8 years since i became aware, as a kid, that not everyone was like this, and the subsequent decade i’ve spent outside the school system and now learning how to help kids like me, i have yet to come up with an excuse for my teachers. you knew. you should have said.

i needed you to see me so badly. i needed someone to tell me they saw my brain was different, or that they were worried bad things were happening to me. i know you noticed. why didn’t you ask? why didn’t you tell the principal that i needed services? why? 24/?

you noticed me sobbing silently in class. you let me stay in your office bc i told you, once, that the cafeteria “hurt my brain.” you asked why i didn’t eat.

why did none of you refer me? why don’t i have an iep? why did you decide i wasn’t high-needs enough? 23/?

sometimes i think about my teachers and a well of rageful, violently painful questions explodes out of my rib cage. you all must have known. you praised my abilities and told my mom i was useless because i didn’t speak. you dumped out my messy desk and called me a lazy brat. 22/?

i have to mourn my little self. my mom tried so hard to raise me well and just didn’t have the tools to help me. my dad worked so hard to make money and he wasn’t around much. that’s nobody’s fault. 21/?

or have a safe place in school, or have help adjusting to the real world. 

i crashed & burned. me & my smarts failed out of college twice. i literally could not function. there were no transition services, no explanation of the magic that made the adults & their world work 20/?

i could have used so much of what i’m learning. social stories would have been great. an adult who didn’t yell at me for balling up in anxiety at the idea of coming inside or leaving my bed. being allowed to stim, or read in class, or take anxiety or adhd meds, 19/?

how did a psychiatrist tell my mom i had a sensory processing disorder and that i’d never be normal without noticing the repetitive finger movements, how i never made eye contact, the way i cried and raged at small noises, and never say “maybe she has autism”? 18/?

correctly because the sensory input and risk was too much, practiced facial expressions in the mirror for hours, recited dialogue from books and movies to practice my speech patterns.

how did no one notice? how did this escape everyone? 17/?

(except for trauma bc why remember that?), and i was miserable. awkward, silent, miserable, suicidal. everything was a colossal effort and a huge risk. i pulled out my hair, cut, lined up my stuffies, didn’t feel pain the way i was supposed to, couldn’t feed or bathe myself 16/?

got one full ride & scholarships for being smart, never had to concentrate on reading (i dunno how to explain this, but i read so painfully fast. whole textbooks in a few hours), played multiple instruments, remembered everything i ever read & everything around me 15/?

i was so smart. i was reading at a high school level in 2nd grade bc all i did was go outside and read bc “no input except this, am safe.” i aced every test, wrote giant papers in one night (my first published academic work as an adult was written largely in two days), 14/?

that somehow everyone knew they were fated to be friends & they acted this way & that way & never had to think about it. i ended up being a prolonged sexual violence victim by my peers (autistic people are 4x more likely to be victimized). but no friends. 13/?

i never had friends. (i have one friend from elementary school who managed to see past the crazy once i was masking better in high school. she’s great.) i literally could not fathom how people interacted with each other. it seemed like everyone was magic except me, 12/?

i consistently, constantly end up living in mess because i cannot stand the sensory input of cleaning. my teenage room looked like a hoarder’s house. i had tics (still do) and echolocalia (still do). 11/?

inside, i screamed and cried because the dog’s bell would jingle when she licked her paws. at night, i would wrap my head in blankets & pillows so i couldn’t hear my house or my dad’s snores. i used to run away from the dinner table bc of the sounds my dad made while eating. 10/?

i was so happy outside. it was so quiet. no one talked to me. it was so free of sensory input. i could bring books outside & not have to talk for literal hours. i tried to stay outside in subfreezing weather and well into the night bc “inside” meant things that made me upset. 9/?

i couldn’t eat except one flavor of poptart, white milk, kraft mac & cheese, pb&j, & canned chicken noodle soup with the chicken taken out for a decade. not a few months of being picky; severe texture abhorrence to the point where my mom gave up & just fed me so i would eat. 8/?

i literally didn’t speak as a child. i could, but i wouldn’t. i threw screaming fits about my socks so often that my mom had to special order ones without seams, and could only buy certain blends of cotton. (i still touch clothes before even taking them off the rack.) 7/?

screaming “my programming doesn’t work, i’m missing whole paragraphs of code” into the void for 25 years & hearing back, every time, that i was just too emotional nearly killed me. nothing anyone ever did or said made sense. of course i was emotional. 6/?
yes, i grew up functioning as a girl & that brings a ✨host✨ of internalized misogyny & socialization, but it doesn’t change my brain’s structure. 5/?

AFABs are automatically assumed to have emotional issues. AMABs are automatically assumed to have “programming” (brain or chemical structure) issues. it’s an extension of the patriarchal system. we all can have both, or one, or neither. our brains are not separate species. 4/?

AFAB people are chronically underdiagnosed for any disorder presumed to be a result of brain structure malfunctions/deficits. i have adhd and am autistic. both are diagnosed 4x more often in AMAB people. our brains are not that different. it’s just no one notices girls. 3/?

reading about myself in these new, enlightened (but not enlightened enough) textbooks and getting ready to service students like me is killing me. why did no one notice? why? everything was there. you all had 12 years. why did no one notice me struggling? 2/?

clearing my head: i’m an AFAB, queer, autistic enby who got a lotta diagnoses (bpd, spd, gad, ocd, adhd) before being diagnosed autistic in my mid-20s bc “girls don’t have autism.” i’m also a teacher, minor in teaching reading, getting a master’s in learning disabilities. 1/?
